WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.425 align:middle line:90%
[SWOOSH]

00:00:01.425 --> 00:00:04.750 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.750 --> 00:00:08.075 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:08.075 --> 00:00:08.863 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.863 --> 00:00:10.530 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA MEREDITH:
As a neuroscientist,

00:00:10.530 --> 00:00:13.300 align:middle line:84%
when someone says, oh, no,
we're only using 5 or 10%

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:14.100 align:middle line:90%
of the brain.

00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:15.430 align:middle line:90%
What's actually going on?

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:17.680 align:middle line:84%
>> TARA SWART: We don't talk
about hardwiring anymore.

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:19.830 align:middle line:84%
We talk about
softwiring, which means

00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:22.530 align:middle line:84%
that even something that's
been there for a very long time

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:25.680 align:middle line:84%
can be, not undone,
but overwritten.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:28.950 align:middle line:84%
I still see so many people,
including high-powered people,

00:00:28.950 --> 00:00:31.890 align:middle line:84%
that are not doing these
basic things, which is rest,

00:00:31.890 --> 00:00:35.190 align:middle line:84%
fuel, hydrate,
oxygenate, and simplify.

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:37.650 align:middle line:84%
Your brain is a tiny
percentage of your whole body.

00:00:37.650 --> 00:00:40.110 align:middle line:84%
But it's a very
energy-hungry organ.

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:44.010 align:middle line:84%
It's using up 20% of what you
eat today when you're asleep.

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:46.950 align:middle line:84%
With your unlimited
brain potential,

00:00:46.950 --> 00:00:50.490 align:middle line:84%
you can take agency
and prime your brain

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:53.160 align:middle line:84%
to go out into the real
world and notice and grasp

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:56.023 align:middle line:84%
opportunities to bring
those things closer to you.

00:00:56.023 --> 00:00:58.338 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:58.338 --> 00:00:59.730 align:middle line:10%


00:00:59.730 --> 00:01:02.070 align:middle line:10%
>> REGINA: My guest
today, Dr. Tara Swart,

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:05.519 align:middle line:10%
is going to tell you about the
neurological science behind why

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:08.730 align:middle line:10%
your favorite practices, such as
vision boards and visualization

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:10.200 align:middle line:10%
in general, work.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:12.420 align:middle line:84%
This means, next time a
friend or family member

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:15.090 align:middle line:84%
pokes fun at you for
your positive practices,

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:17.550 align:middle line:84%
you can read them
in on the science.

00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:19.900 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for joining us today.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:21.120 align:middle line:90%
It's just lovely to see you.

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:22.170 align:middle line:90%
And I have your book.

00:01:22.170 --> 00:01:24.510 align:middle line:10%
It has at least 100
dog-eared pages,

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:26.220 align:middle line:10%
which is like every other page.

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:28.170 align:middle line:10%
You really are now
bridging the gap

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:31.200 align:middle line:10%
between the world of
neuroscience and the practices

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:34.230 align:middle line:10%
that we've all participated
in over the last 30, 40

00:01:34.230 --> 00:01:38.170 align:middle line:10%
years the evolution of
human consciousness.

00:01:38.170 --> 00:01:40.080 align:middle line:84%
And so I just want
to applaud you

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:41.920 align:middle line:90%
for doing the hard work for us.

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:45.900 align:middle line:84%
I think yours is really now
the primer on how to use

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:48.820 align:middle line:90%
the brain to a better effect.

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:50.505 align:middle line:90%
So first, welcome.

00:01:50.505 --> 00:01:53.130 align:middle line:10%
>> SWART: Thank you so much for
having me and for acknowledging

00:01:53.130 --> 00:01:55.510 align:middle line:10%
that because, at one
point in my career,

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:57.210 align:middle line:10%
it did feel like
a bit of a risk.

00:01:57.210 --> 00:02:00.360 align:middle line:84%
As a professor at
MIT, I wanted to start

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:03.180 align:middle line:84%
sharing my personal
beliefs about spirituality.

00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:06.480 align:middle line:10%
And, after a crisis
in my own life,

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:09.210 align:middle line:10%
I'd managed to merge
those really successfully,

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:12.120 align:middle line:10%
the science and
the spirituality.

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:14.040 align:middle line:84%
And, actually,
writing "The Source"

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:15.630 align:middle line:84%
and having it come
out into the world

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:18.180 align:middle line:84%
was probably that
last step that really

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:21.090 align:middle line:84%
made me feel like, yes,
these two things can coexist.

00:02:21.090 --> 00:02:24.090 align:middle line:84%
And not only can they,
but it's so, so important

00:02:24.090 --> 00:02:27.120 align:middle line:84%
for people to understand
and leverage that.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:29.130 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It's not
just, can they coexist?

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:29.970 align:middle line:90%
They do coexist.

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:30.770 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: I know.

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:34.950 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: We just had
everything so partitioned

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:37.200 align:middle line:84%
in our understanding
of how mind works.

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:39.660 align:middle line:84%
And you've allowed all
of it to come together,

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:43.313 align:middle line:84%
but to explain it in a
scientific way why it works.

00:02:43.313 --> 00:02:44.730 align:middle line:84%
So let's start
with your childhood

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:47.790 align:middle line:84%
because you were raised
in England, in London.

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:50.550 align:middle line:84%
But you came from East
Indian parents and heritage.

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:52.950 align:middle line:84%
And they still had some
of their practices,

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:56.410 align:middle line:84%
which you weren't initially
proud of, especially

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:57.210 align:middle line:90%
as a teenager.

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:59.880 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about that
and how that influenced you.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:02.850 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: Yeah, so what I feel
is that, when people emigrate,

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:05.670 align:middle line:84%
they actually hold on to their
traditions even more strongly

00:03:05.670 --> 00:03:07.920 align:middle line:84%
than people that remain
in the original country.

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:11.910 align:middle line:84%
So things like my
cousins eat meat,

00:03:11.910 --> 00:03:15.000 align:middle line:84%
but I was brought up
completely vegetarian.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.830 align:middle line:90%
And, yeah, the classic things.

00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:18.570 align:middle line:84%
We had like the
chanting and the incense

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:21.600 align:middle line:84%
sticks and the meditation and
the yoga and the breathwork.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:23.260 align:middle line:90%
I was brought up with that.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:27.810 align:middle line:84%
And it became popular in
Western culture decades later.

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:30.570 align:middle line:84%
And I just wanted
to fit in at school.

00:03:30.570 --> 00:03:32.575 align:middle line:84%
I didn't-- nobody
else's parents.

00:03:32.575 --> 00:03:34.950 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: You didn't want to
smell like incense when you

00:03:34.950 --> 00:03:35.980 align:middle line:90%
came in the classroom.

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:36.780 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Or curry.

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:37.613 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Or curry.

00:03:37.613 --> 00:03:38.490 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHING]

00:03:38.490 --> 00:03:41.370 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So, yeah, I guess
there was a period of time that

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:42.840 align:middle line:90%
I rejected those things.

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:45.550 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I had to
come full circle.

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:48.210 align:middle line:84%
But what I really did
was I separated them.

00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:50.250 align:middle line:84%
So I had one life
at home and one life

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:52.380 align:middle line:90%
at school and with my friends.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:55.840 align:middle line:84%
And it took a certain
level of maturity.

00:03:55.840 --> 00:04:00.130 align:middle line:84%
But then it also actually
took a personal crisis for me

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:03.940 align:middle line:84%
to really think about, well,
I need elements of both.

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:06.580 align:middle line:84%
And that kind of
started the journey

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:08.488 align:middle line:90%
of the career change and then--

00:04:08.488 --> 00:04:10.030 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: The
integration of these--

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:11.113 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: The integration.

00:04:11.113 --> 00:04:13.690 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So you became a
teenage little fashionista

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:16.670 align:middle line:84%
and things like this,
what girls do in London,

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:19.329 align:middle line:90%
great place to be a fashionista.

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:24.160 align:middle line:84%
But you decided to get a
degree in neuroscience.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.420 align:middle line:84%
And, also, as I
recall, psychology, you

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:31.113 align:middle line:84%
were working with
psychology and neuroscience.

00:04:31.113 --> 00:04:32.530 align:middle line:84%
How did that go
in your education?

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:35.072 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: The way that it works
in the UK is a bit different.

00:04:35.072 --> 00:04:38.950 align:middle line:84%
And, actually, when
I went to university,

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:41.950 align:middle line:84%
you couldn't-- neuroscience
itself wasn't a degree.

00:04:41.950 --> 00:04:44.803 align:middle line:84%
So we can go straight from
high school to medical school.

00:04:44.803 --> 00:04:45.970 align:middle line:90%
So I went to medical school.

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:48.370 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Oh, without the
interim four years we have

00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:49.185 align:middle line:90%
in America.

00:04:49.185 --> 00:04:49.985 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:04:49.985 --> 00:04:53.380 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So we have the
theoretical three years.

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.180 align:middle line:90%
And it's called preclinical.

00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:57.820 align:middle line:84%
And then you-- well,
it's actually two.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.890 align:middle line:84%
But you can do special
topics in the third year.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:02.110 align:middle line:84%
And I chose the neuro
of every topic--

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:04.450 align:middle line:84%
neuroanatomy, neuropharmacology,
neurophysiology.

00:05:04.450 --> 00:05:05.590 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Interesting, OK.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:07.548 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: I was just so
fascinated by the brain

00:05:07.548 --> 00:05:10.320 align:middle line:84%
and the mind, which was still
seen as quite separate at that

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:11.120 align:middle line:90%
point.

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:13.480 align:middle line:90%
So I did my PhD in neuroscience.

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:15.490 align:middle line:84%
I took three years
out to do that.

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:17.650 align:middle line:84%
Then I came back
to medical school

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:19.150 align:middle line:90%
and did clinical practice.

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:21.025 align:middle line:84%
I thought I wanted to
become a neurologist,

00:05:21.025 --> 00:05:22.900 align:middle line:84%
but I decided to become
a psychiatrist, which

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:26.170 align:middle line:84%
is an MD, as opposed
to a psychologist.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:29.260 align:middle line:84%
And I worked as a
psychiatrist for seven years.

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:32.353 align:middle line:84%
And then I decided to change
career at around the same time

00:05:32.353 --> 00:05:33.520 align:middle line:90%
that I was getting divorced.

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:35.860 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So how old would
you have been at that time

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:39.580 align:middle line:84%
because the difference in the
way the years are calculated

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:41.000 align:middle line:90%
in your educational system.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.125 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So I went to
university at the age of 18.

00:05:43.125 --> 00:05:45.430 align:middle line:84%
And I was at university
for nine years.

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:47.410 align:middle line:84%
And I came out with
an MD and a PhD.

00:05:47.410 --> 00:05:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So you're 27 years
old when you entered the work

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:51.120 align:middle line:90%
world as a psychiatrist.

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:51.920 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Yes.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:54.430 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: And then you were
working with the national

00:05:54.430 --> 00:05:55.810 align:middle line:90%
health care system.

00:05:55.810 --> 00:05:57.430 align:middle line:90%
So there are certain guidelines.

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:00.040 align:middle line:84%
And so you were allowed
to throw lots of pills

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:01.240 align:middle line:90%
at people if need be.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:02.152 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Oh, yes.

00:06:02.152 --> 00:06:04.360 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So you could toss
them their prescriptions

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:05.170 align:middle line:90%
and their pills.

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:06.937 align:middle line:84%
But they weren't getting
better in the way

00:06:06.937 --> 00:06:09.020 align:middle line:84%
that you would like to
have seen for your clients.

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:10.810 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about
your experience

00:06:10.810 --> 00:06:14.470 align:middle line:84%
as a young and, at this time,
compassionate and idealistic

00:06:14.470 --> 00:06:16.895 align:middle line:90%
young psychiatrist.

00:06:16.895 --> 00:06:18.770 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: Thank you for
asking that question.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:22.000 align:middle line:84%
So all I did was
diagnose and prescribe.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.150 align:middle line:84%
And, even though I was into
healthy eating and exercise,

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:29.800 align:middle line:84%
it could be mentioned,
but it certainly

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:33.400 align:middle line:84%
wasn't part of the holistic way
that our patients were treated.

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:37.380 align:middle line:84%
And I cared a great
deal about my patients.

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:39.600 align:middle line:84%
But I couldn't stay
in that system.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.260 align:middle line:84%
I didn't feel like I would
be giving the best of myself

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:45.970 align:middle line:84%
to the world if I
stayed in that system.

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:49.218 align:middle line:84%
And so I got to the
point where-- in the NHS,

00:06:49.218 --> 00:06:50.760 align:middle line:84%
you're really dealing
with the lowest

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:54.360 align:middle line:90%
socioeconomic group of people.

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:56.280 align:middle line:84%
Usually, their families
have deserted them.

00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:57.180 align:middle line:90%
They don't have partners.

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:58.847 align:middle line:84%
Their children are
taken away from them.

00:06:58.847 --> 00:07:00.480 align:middle line:90%
They can't hold down a job.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.310 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, OK,
what could I really do

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:07.950 align:middle line:84%
to make life better for these
people in a very different way?

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:10.230 align:middle line:84%
And the first part
of that step was

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:13.560 align:middle line:84%
to go and work with businesses,
with really influential people

00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:16.350 align:middle line:84%
that have corporate social
responsibility and teams

00:07:16.350 --> 00:07:19.330 align:middle line:84%
and families and kind of work
through that cascade effect.

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:21.750 align:middle line:84%
And then, as you know,
the latest iteration

00:07:21.750 --> 00:07:24.990 align:middle line:84%
has been much more about
being on social media,

00:07:24.990 --> 00:07:26.730 align:middle line:84%
having my podcast,
writing my book,

00:07:26.730 --> 00:07:29.540 align:middle line:84%
and trying to spread that
information as excessively--

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:30.540 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Far and wide.

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:31.800 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: --as possible.

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:33.510 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: So you went along.

00:07:33.510 --> 00:07:35.790 align:middle line:84%
And there came a
point in your life.

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:38.130 align:middle line:84%
You were feeling
this dissatisfaction.

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:39.120 align:middle line:90%
Let me just ask you.

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.790 align:middle line:84%
When you're sitting with
someone whose life is so broken,

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:45.990 align:middle line:84%
whose health is in such poor
shape mentally and physically,

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:48.240 align:middle line:84%
did you feel like
if you could just

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:50.190 align:middle line:84%
take time out and
away from everything

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:52.080 align:middle line:84%
and be with this
person, you could really

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:53.898 align:middle line:90%
do something for them?

00:07:53.898 --> 00:07:56.190 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: You're giving me
goosebumps because it's been

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:57.840 align:middle line:84%
so long since I was
in that position.

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:00.750 align:middle line:84%
But I remember always saying
if I could bottle a loving

00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:03.840 align:middle line:90%
partner, I'd be out of a job.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:05.910 align:middle line:84%
So the few patients
that did have

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:09.540 align:middle line:84%
somebody that really stuck by
them through the tough times

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:11.880 align:middle line:84%
and in the good times and
helped them to make sure

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:13.470 align:middle line:84%
that they stayed
on their medication

00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:15.570 align:middle line:84%
or practiced the
healthy life habits,

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:17.760 align:middle line:84%
there was a huge difference
between those people

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.370 align:middle line:84%
and the people that had
nobody that cared about them

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:26.640 align:middle line:84%
and, therefore, no real purpose
other than just surviving.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:30.750 align:middle line:84%
And, yeah, absolutely, there's
just always some patients

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:32.159 align:middle line:90%
that you fall in love with.

00:08:32.159 --> 00:08:34.409 align:middle line:84%
And you have a special
relationship with their family.

00:08:34.409 --> 00:08:37.110 align:middle line:84%
And you think if I
could take you home,

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:39.179 align:middle line:84%
you'd never have to go
to the hospital again.

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:40.539 align:middle line:90%
There is that element of that.

00:08:40.539 --> 00:08:41.610 align:middle line:84%
But you can't do
that for everyone.

00:08:41.610 --> 00:08:42.120 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: No, you can't.

00:08:42.120 --> 00:08:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And I ask because this is
a growing phenomena right

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:45.870 align:middle line:90%
now certainly in America.

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:47.880 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how it's
handled in England.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:49.470 align:middle line:90%
But I live in California.

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:52.020 align:middle line:84%
And we're known-- we make
headlines in the news

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:54.480 align:middle line:84%
for our homeless situation,
which is usually--

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:57.360 align:middle line:84%
has a great deal to do with
mental illness and people who

00:08:57.360 --> 00:08:59.850 align:middle line:90%
aren't able to hang on anymore.

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:03.510 align:middle line:84%
And no one knows-- they don't
know-- there's no system really

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:06.420 align:middle line:90%
in place for that.

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:08.490 align:middle line:84%
And you're right--
there isn't a partner.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:10.560 align:middle line:84%
These people don't
have a loving partner.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:12.060 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: It's totally heart--
it's totally heartbreaking.

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:14.018 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: The partner,
if they have a partner,

00:09:14.018 --> 00:09:16.300 align:middle line:84%
it's usually their dog,
which is better than--

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:17.100 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Nothing.

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:18.720 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Absolutely.

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.290 align:middle line:84%
OK, so, in your own life,
you had some breakdowns

00:09:21.290 --> 00:09:22.090 align:middle line:90%
of your own.

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:24.310 align:middle line:84%
So you're going along, and
you're a little hotshot

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:25.110 align:middle line:90%
doing your thing.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:26.580 align:middle line:90%
You're a little brokenhearted.

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:27.540 align:middle line:90%
You can't do more.

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:29.730 align:middle line:90%
And you're married.

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:31.060 align:middle line:90%
OK, now what happens?

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:33.430 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So I was married
to somebody who was also

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:34.230 align:middle line:90%
a psychiatrist.

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.090 align:middle line:90%
So we worked together.

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:39.790 align:middle line:84%
And we'd met quite young, and we
were from different countries.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:40.590 align:middle line:90%
He's South African.

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:42.382 align:middle line:84%
We're actually very,
very good friends now.

00:09:42.382 --> 00:09:46.380 align:middle line:84%
But I think, in those
formative years, from 25 to 35,

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:48.910 align:middle line:84%
we just grew into
very different people.

00:09:48.910 --> 00:09:52.600 align:middle line:84%
And I had already started
thinking about changing career.

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:54.750 align:middle line:84%
And it was so
interesting looking back

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:57.150 align:middle line:84%
that people thought
it was really strange

00:09:57.150 --> 00:09:58.950 align:middle line:84%
that I would give up
being a medical doctor

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.550 align:middle line:90%
to become a coach.

00:10:00.550 --> 00:10:03.240 align:middle line:84%
And so I was challenged on
that on an almost daily basis.

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:05.243 align:middle line:84%
And I realized that
I had to come up

00:10:05.243 --> 00:10:06.660 align:middle line:84%
with a really good
answer to that.

00:10:06.660 --> 00:10:10.830 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, it was going to start
affecting my own idea of what

00:10:10.830 --> 00:10:12.210 align:middle line:90%
I should be doing and who I am.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:16.270 align:middle line:84%
And, like we said, in the
UK, you go to medical school

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:17.070 align:middle line:90%
when you're 18.

00:10:17.070 --> 00:10:20.940 align:middle line:84%
Your entire adult life is
associated with that identity,

00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:22.487 align:middle line:90%
that you're a doctor.

00:10:22.487 --> 00:10:23.820 align:middle line:90%
And I didn't know anything else.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:25.990 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't think I
could do anything else.

00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:27.870 align:middle line:84%
So I had to start
saying to people,

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:29.610 align:middle line:84%
no, the reason I
think it's better

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:31.650 align:middle line:84%
that I'm going to do what
I'm going to go and do

00:10:31.650 --> 00:10:33.480 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit
like I said to you--

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:36.990 align:middle line:90%
I can have a bigger impact.

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:40.560 align:middle line:84%
And I think that kind of
widened the gap between us

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:42.450 align:middle line:84%
because it felt like
what I was saying was,

00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:44.530 align:middle line:84%
your job isn't good
enough for me anymore.

00:10:44.530 --> 00:10:47.880 align:middle line:84%
And I can go and do
something better.

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:50.460 align:middle line:84%
So he was still very
supportive in terms

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:52.710 align:middle line:84%
of we'd agreed that if
I gave up my job that I

00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:57.060 align:middle line:84%
would need a bit of help
to get started again.

00:10:57.060 --> 00:10:59.250 align:middle line:84%
But I found myself
in my mid-30s,

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:01.710 align:middle line:84%
having been married,
suddenly single,

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:03.510 align:middle line:84%
having been a
doctor-- and that was

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:05.670 align:middle line:84%
a very strong part
of my identity--

00:11:05.670 --> 00:11:08.640 align:middle line:84%
not really knowing
what I was anymore.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:10.690 align:middle line:84%
We'd also lived abroad
a couple of times.

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:12.570 align:middle line:84%
So we'd worked in
Australia and in Bermuda.

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:16.260 align:middle line:84%
So I came back home to London
to start my new career.

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:18.720 align:middle line:84%
But I had to find a
place to live on my own

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:22.350 align:middle line:84%
again and reintegrate
with my school friends.

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:24.120 align:middle line:84%
So it was a real
period of transition.

00:11:24.120 --> 00:11:28.530 align:middle line:84%
And, at that time, I was
drawn to Jungian psychology

00:11:28.530 --> 00:11:30.240 align:middle line:90%
and Buddhist philosophy.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:32.790 align:middle line:84%
Those were just the
two things that I

00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:36.120 align:middle line:84%
became super interested in and
went down a rabbit hole with.

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:39.600 align:middle line:84%
And they seemed to make
sense together to me

00:11:39.600 --> 00:11:42.630 align:middle line:84%
and those were the
essences and concepts

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:45.210 align:middle line:84%
that helped me to come out
of that very dark place

00:11:45.210 --> 00:11:47.455 align:middle line:90%
that I was in for a while.

00:11:47.455 --> 00:11:49.830 align:middle line:84%
And I think that must have
stuck with me when I came back

00:11:49.830 --> 00:11:51.247 align:middle line:84%
to write "The
Source" because it's

00:11:51.247 --> 00:11:54.640 align:middle line:84%
kind of psychological but
also Eastern spirituality.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:56.850 align:middle line:84%
So that's definitely been
a theme because I think--

00:11:56.850 --> 00:11:57.810 align:middle line:90%
I was 35 then.

00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:01.350 align:middle line:84%
So it was seven, eight years
later that I wrote the book.

00:12:01.350 --> 00:12:02.790 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Right, so tell us.

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:05.370 align:middle line:84%
What is-- before we go into
the rest of the story--

00:12:05.370 --> 00:12:07.500 align:middle line:90%
what is "the source?"

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.820 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So the source,
obviously, has very,

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:14.460 align:middle line:84%
very strong spiritual
connotations in terms of being

00:12:14.460 --> 00:12:15.352 align:middle line:90%
whatever--

00:12:15.352 --> 00:12:17.310 align:middle line:84%
however you call it, God,
the universe, spirit.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:20.590 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: This is a very
open-minded audience.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:21.550 align:middle line:90%
Any term you wish.

00:12:21.550 --> 00:12:24.450 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: And so any term
that each of us wishes.

00:12:24.450 --> 00:12:26.880 align:middle line:84%
But it's basically
the place that all

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:29.640 align:middle line:84%
of that spiritual energy comes
from that we can tap into,

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:33.570 align:middle line:84%
that means that
we're all connected.

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:37.440 align:middle line:84%
But I took that word, with
all of those connotations,

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:40.440 align:middle line:84%
and said, basically,
for you, it's

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:42.990 align:middle line:84%
your brainpower
and the potential

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:45.130 align:middle line:84%
that you hold that
you haven't used yet.

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:48.330 align:middle line:84%
So it's both of those things,
the spiritual and the fact

00:12:48.330 --> 00:12:51.150 align:middle line:84%
that, in your own
brain, unless you're

00:12:51.150 --> 00:12:53.370 align:middle line:84%
a neuroscientist and
an MD, you probably

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:55.950 align:middle line:84%
don't know how
incredible your brain is.

00:12:55.950 --> 00:12:58.020 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Absolutely,
so we always hear, well,

00:12:58.020 --> 00:13:01.240 align:middle line:84%
we're only using, oh,
about 10% of the brain.

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:04.560 align:middle line:84%
Now that's-- we're
talking brain versus mind,

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:05.760 align:middle line:90%
a whole different subject.

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:08.440 align:middle line:84%
So, as a neuroscientist,
when someone says,

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:11.940 align:middle line:84%
oh no, we're only using,
oh, 5 or 10% of the brain.

00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:14.070 align:middle line:90%
What's actually going on?

00:13:14.070 --> 00:13:16.260 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: OK, so it doesn't
quite work like that.

00:13:16.260 --> 00:13:18.630 align:middle line:90%
So you've got your brain.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:22.470 align:middle line:84%
The emotional part is about
the size of your clenched fist.

00:13:22.470 --> 00:13:24.210 align:middle line:84%
And then the more
logical systems

00:13:24.210 --> 00:13:27.120 align:middle line:84%
are around that in about
the same kind of width.

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:29.370 align:middle line:84%
But it's all systems
and subsystems

00:13:29.370 --> 00:13:31.270 align:middle line:84%
that have cascade
effects with each other.

00:13:31.270 --> 00:13:33.090 align:middle line:84%
It's not like this
part of your brain

00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:35.340 align:middle line:84%
is for reading and writing
and that part of your brain

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:37.860 align:middle line:90%
is for vision.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:41.370 align:middle line:84%
So it may be that, when you're
sitting here interviewing,

00:13:41.370 --> 00:13:43.590 align:middle line:84%
as a very experienced
person, you're

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:47.010 align:middle line:84%
accessing a 10% of your brain
that's just honed into this

00:13:47.010 --> 00:13:49.080 align:middle line:90%
being an expert at this task.

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:51.670 align:middle line:84%
But you can access
all of your brain,

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:54.510 align:middle line:84%
but you don't need
to all the time.

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:58.020 align:middle line:84%
So it's really about
maybe accessing parts

00:13:58.020 --> 00:14:00.360 align:middle line:84%
that you don't use all
the time to just increase

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:04.230 align:middle line:84%
your field of what you
can do, maybe using

00:14:04.230 --> 00:14:06.210 align:middle line:84%
different parts of the
brain at the same time

00:14:06.210 --> 00:14:08.580 align:middle line:84%
together more often
than we have to.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:12.690 align:middle line:84%
And just really accessing
all of the potential

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:15.892 align:middle line:84%
that you have because the
brain is very energy efficient.

00:14:15.892 --> 00:14:17.850 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: That's what
I was just going to ask.

00:14:17.850 --> 00:14:20.580 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: So it won't do that
unless you override it and say,

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:22.577 align:middle line:84%
but I want to bring
in my creativity.

00:14:22.577 --> 00:14:23.910 align:middle line:90%
I want to bring in my curiosity.

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:25.380 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It's always
going to conserve energy.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:26.490 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Exactly.

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:28.560 align:middle line:84%
So the things you're
really good at,

00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:31.170 align:middle line:84%
those are the easiest
things for your brain to do.

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.300 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So now let's
talk about another myth.

00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:37.075 align:middle line:84%
And that is, well, it's a shame
what's happening because--

00:14:37.075 --> 00:14:38.700 align:middle line:84%
especially when you
see little children

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:42.570 align:middle line:84%
that aren't having the best
programming in their youth--

00:14:42.570 --> 00:14:43.860 align:middle line:90%
say it's a shame.

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:45.450 align:middle line:90%
It's all done by seven.

00:14:45.450 --> 00:14:46.830 align:middle line:90%
We are who we are.

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:49.020 align:middle line:84%
That's when all the
development happens.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:52.580 align:middle line:84%
Myth, so let's go ahead
and bust that myth.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:54.080 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: I love
busting neuromyths.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:56.730 align:middle line:90%
So this is good.

00:14:56.730 --> 00:14:58.170 align:middle line:90%
So there's a couple of things.

00:14:58.170 --> 00:14:59.820 align:middle line:84%
We used to think
that, by the time

00:14:59.820 --> 00:15:02.850 align:middle line:84%
you physically stop
growing, so roughly 18,

00:15:02.850 --> 00:15:05.070 align:middle line:84%
that that's kind of
when your brain is set.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:08.940 align:middle line:84%
But a subset of that is that
the things that you experience

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:11.280 align:middle line:84%
by the age of seven
have the biggest

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:14.240 align:middle line:84%
impact on your personality
and how you're triggered

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:15.990 align:middle line:84%
and how you respond
to things for the rest

00:15:15.990 --> 00:15:18.200 align:middle line:90%
of your emotional life.

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:22.270 align:middle line:84%
So it's not untrue that
the longer a pathway

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:23.860 align:middle line:90%
has been in your brain--

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:26.080 align:middle line:84%
so neurons that fire
together wire together.

00:15:26.080 --> 00:15:27.550 align:middle line:84%
The more you
experience something,

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:28.810 align:middle line:90%
that becomes more entrenched--

00:15:28.810 --> 00:15:31.030 align:middle line:84%
an entrenched pathway
in your brain.

00:15:31.030 --> 00:15:33.910 align:middle line:84%
It's not untrue that the
longer it's been there,

00:15:33.910 --> 00:15:36.850 align:middle line:84%
the more subconsciously
that will play out.

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:39.590 align:middle line:84%
But we don't talk about
hardwiring anymore.

00:15:39.590 --> 00:15:41.740 align:middle line:84%
We talk about
softwiring, which means

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:44.680 align:middle line:84%
that even something that's
been there for a very long time

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:49.070 align:middle line:84%
can be, not undone,
but overwritten.

00:15:49.070 --> 00:15:51.220 align:middle line:84%
So I'm being very, very
precise with my words

00:15:51.220 --> 00:15:55.985 align:middle line:84%
here because I could just
say, no, that's not true--

00:15:55.985 --> 00:15:57.610 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: I like
the word overwritten,

00:15:57.610 --> 00:15:59.140 align:middle line:90%
to overwrite a program.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:01.690 align:middle line:84%
>> SWART: Because you can't
actually undo a pathway

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:02.660 align:middle line:90%
in your brain.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:06.760 align:middle line:84%
But if you replace it with
a new desired thought that--

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:09.290 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: That's stronger.

00:16:09.290 --> 00:16:10.210 align:middle line:90%
Do they compete?

00:16:10.210 --> 00:16:11.210 align:middle line:90%
How does that work then?

00:16:11.210 --> 00:16:11.910 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: They compete.

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:13.620 align:middle line:84%
So the one that's been
there for longer--

00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:15.230 align:middle line:84%
this is why that
myth comes about.

00:16:15.230 --> 00:16:16.850 align:middle line:84%
The one that's
been there already

00:16:16.850 --> 00:16:19.230 align:middle line:90%
is the energy-efficient pathway.

00:16:19.230 --> 00:16:21.890 align:middle line:84%
So there's two things
that can overwrite that--

00:16:21.890 --> 00:16:25.460 align:middle line:84%
repetition and
emotional intensity.

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:28.020 align:middle line:84%
So repetition we can
control quite easily.

00:16:28.020 --> 00:16:32.600 align:middle line:84%
So let's say you have a
belief that you were just

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:35.120 align:middle line:84%
like your grandmother, these
sorts of things that get

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:37.580 align:middle line:84%
said to people before
the age of seven.

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:42.170 align:middle line:84%
If you repeatedly, every time
that comes up, say to yourself,

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:44.040 align:middle line:90%
actually, I'm my own person.

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:47.750 align:middle line:84%
I may have elements
that resemble

00:16:47.750 --> 00:16:49.170 align:middle line:90%
other people in my family.

00:16:49.170 --> 00:16:50.510 align:middle line:90%
But I can be my own person.

00:16:50.510 --> 00:16:54.590 align:middle line:84%
If you say that every day, 10
times a day, at some point,

00:16:54.590 --> 00:16:57.200 align:middle line:84%
that's going to override
this belief that you held.

00:16:57.200 --> 00:17:01.220 align:middle line:84%
The emotional intensity
one is harder to create.

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:03.680 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: It's almost like
it comes in the form of trauma

00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:04.480 align:middle line:90%
oftentimes.

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:05.967 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: Trauma or--

00:17:05.967 --> 00:17:06.800 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Surprise.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:07.925 align:middle line:90%
>> SWART: So surprise.

00:17:07.925 --> 00:17:09.734 align:middle line:84%
I mean, traumatic--
if you and I went

00:17:09.734 --> 00:17:11.359 align:middle line:84%
through a traumatic
incident together--

00:17:11.359 --> 00:17:13.740 align:middle line:84%
let's say something suddenly
happened in this building--

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:16.045 align:middle line:84%
we would bond
emotionally much more

00:17:16.045 --> 00:17:18.170 align:middle line:84%
than if we just did this
interview and nothing went

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:19.339 align:middle line:90%
wrong.

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:23.280 align:middle line:84%
So it is-- but what
you can do is--

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:25.730 align:middle line:84%
I know we're going to come on
to talk about visualization

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:31.090 align:middle line:84%
and manifestation is you can
create an image that's very

00:17:31.090 --> 00:17:35.770 align:middle line:84%
emotionally important to you
about why you cannot continue

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:38.950 align:middle line:84%
the rest of your life
believing that you're just

00:17:38.950 --> 00:17:40.450 align:middle line:84%
a reincarnation of
your grandmother,

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:43.570 align:middle line:84%
and you've got no chance
to be your own person or be

00:17:43.570 --> 00:17:46.000 align:middle line:90%
different.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.160 align:middle line:84%
So you could do that
with visualization.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.290 align:middle line:90%
You could do it with journaling.

00:17:50.290 --> 00:17:56.270 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: So how can you add
