compare me to my grandmother?

00:18:37.640 --> 00:18:39.470 align:middle line:84%
You might get butterflies
in your stomach

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:43.010 align:middle line:84%
or you might get a closed
feeling in your throat

00:18:43.010 --> 00:18:45.020 align:middle line:90%
or crawling on your skin.

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:47.900 align:middle line:84%
Acknowledging that
too and managing

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:51.080 align:middle line:84%
to soothe yourself to reverse
those physical symptoms.

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:57.350 align:middle line:84%
But the biggest one I would say
is that trauma and to some--

00:18:57.350 --> 00:19:00.620 align:middle line:84%
surprise is kind of in
between on this spectrum

00:19:00.620 --> 00:19:01.820 align:middle line:90%
of basic human emotions.

00:19:01.820 --> 00:19:03.690 align:middle line:90%
You've seen it in the book.

00:19:03.690 --> 00:19:08.900 align:middle line:84%
So, mostly, trauma pushes
us into the stress side

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:09.900 align:middle line:90%
of those emotions.

00:19:09.900 --> 00:19:14.030 align:middle line:84%
So it makes us feel things like
fear, anger, shame, sadness,

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:15.080 align:middle line:90%
disgust.

00:19:15.080 --> 00:19:17.240 align:middle line:84%
And, when we feel
those emotions,

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:20.270 align:middle line:84%
we have higher levels of
the stress hormone cortisol.

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:23.450 align:middle line:84%
And that affects the blood
flow around the brain.

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:25.790 align:middle line:84%
And it affects which
brain pathways really

00:19:25.790 --> 00:19:29.250 align:middle line:84%
come to the fore, so the ones
that were put there by trauma.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:31.700 align:middle line:84%
If you find ways
to move yourself

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:33.650 align:middle line:84%
away from those
emotions to love,

00:19:33.650 --> 00:19:37.460 align:middle line:84%
to trust, to gratitude,
to joy, then you

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:39.410 align:middle line:90%
allow oxytocin to flourish.

00:19:39.410 --> 00:19:41.540 align:middle line:90%
And that's the bonding hormone.

00:19:41.540 --> 00:19:44.450 align:middle line:84%
It makes you feel like
you can lower your guard.

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:46.280 align:middle line:90%
You can take healthy risks.

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:48.110 align:middle line:90%
And that's a lifelong practice.

00:19:48.110 --> 00:19:49.520 align:middle line:90%
That can come through gratitude.

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:51.020 align:middle line:90%
It can come through journaling.

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:53.600 align:middle line:84%
But it has to also
come through--

00:19:53.600 --> 00:19:57.900 align:middle line:84%
when you feel triggered by
your trauma, that you can say,

00:19:57.900 --> 00:19:58.700 align:middle line:90%
I'm safe.

00:19:58.700 --> 00:19:59.500 align:middle line:90%
I'm OK.

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:01.190 align:middle line:84%
That you can control
your breathing,

00:20:01.190 --> 00:20:04.220 align:middle line:84%
